      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "As of now, covert manipulation of audio files to include infrasound with the intention of influencing behavior—or for harmful purposes—isn't a widely reported or technically common practice, in part because psychoacoustic effects of infrasound are not fully understood by mainstream science. Simpler psychoacoustic phenomena are more likely used for emotional impact, such as certain tempos or dissonant chord progressions.\n\nIf one were to explore such technologically advanced audio manipulation, it would involve complex sound design, potentially involving synthesizers capable of generating infrasound frequencies. Advanced audio editing software would be used to mix these frequencies into the track with care, ensuring they don't become too perceptible due to the masking—the natural phenomenon where louder sounds make softer ones harder to hear. Yet, doing so responsibly within ethical boundaries and artistic expression remains hypothetical, and there's no mainstream software specifically advertised for such purposes because it would likely be unethically oriented or for purposes that contradict general good and current laws regarding audio manipulation. However, familiar editing software like Adobe Audition, Ableton Live, and Pro Tools could theoretically be used by a skilled user to experiment with low-frequency sounds, though not likely hidden within commercially released music tracks. It is worth reiterating that this is a theoretical discussion",
